<div id="review_21278688" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/21278688" />
    <a title="Adam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/614339-adam"><img alt="Adam" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/21278688?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam" href="/user/show/614339-adam">Adam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">fans of Master and Margarita</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer21278688" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5412285796230959234">In a nutshell, L&apos;Ecume Des Jours reads like an Edith Wharton novel set in Pepperland (sorry, non-cinephiles for the obscure reference). The book rewires your brain after the first 30 pages; if it doesn&apos;t, this book is not for you. Themes/motifs: class struggle, love, flowers, Sartre, mice, death and cocktails. My favorite image from the book is when the protagonist loses his fortune and takes a job at a weapons factory. You see, though, the rifle barrels are grown from seeds that must be warmed </span>
  <span id="freeText5412285796230959234" style="display:none">In a nutshell, L'Ecume Des Jours reads like an Edith Wharton novel set in Pepperland (sorry, non-cinephiles for the obscure reference). The book rewires your brain after the first 30 pages; if it doesn't, this book is not for you. Themes/motifs: class struggle, love, flowers, Sartre, mice, death and cocktails. My favorite image from the book is when the protagonist loses his fortune and takes a job at a weapons factory. You see, though, the rifle barrels are grown from seeds that must be warmed at 98.6 degrees. You guessed it. Someone has to lie on top of the seeds so they properly germinate. Colin's love for his dying wife, Chloe (who has a waterlily growing in her lung), leads to a bad crop of rifle barrels: they all have a steel flower growing from their tips.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5412285796230959234" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


