    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1895636423" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1895636423" />
    <a title="Aravindakshan Narasimhan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62878026-aravindakshan-narasimhan"><img alt="Aravindakshan Narasimhan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600662048p2/62878026.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1895636423?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aravindakshan Narasimhan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aravindakshan Narasimhan" href="/user/show/62878026-aravindakshan-narasimhan">Aravindakshan Narasimhan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1895636423" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5813691793023571407">Imagine you are sitting in a restaurant on a sultry evening where the trees are protesting not to dance to the tune of nature, and birds do not show their face or call out. You have started your eating adventure with much hope, only to be shattered by the poor reception and ergonomical errors on the side of hotel management, weary faces of servers, unhindered cacophony and to top it all, a poor food. All makes it one nightmarish dining experience already accentuated by your boring day at work. S</span>
  <span id="freeText5813691793023571407" style="display:none">Imagine you are sitting in a restaurant on a sultry evening where the trees are protesting not to dance to the tune of nature, and birds do not show their face or call out. You have started your eating adventure with much hope, only to be shattered by the poor reception and ergonomical errors on the side of hotel management, weary faces of servers, unhindered cacophony and to top it all, a poor food. All makes it one nightmarish dining experience already accentuated by your boring day at work. So when you are almost restless to get out of this nightmare, without you being aware, u order an ice cream.<br /><br />You take the spoon absentmindedly. The lavish and bricolage of colours that try appeasing you through their glass encase does not bring you back to present. You seem to have inserted your spoon inside your mouth now. Just at the moment when it starts to embrace your tongue fully and play with your saliva, you suddenly wake from your slumber. Like a bucket full of ice water that has been made to dance on your face, your eyes turn reddish and you are finally aware that you are sitting inside a restaurant and eating an ice cream!<br /><br />You without giving much thought to its physical charm, pierce the spoon into its toppings and not getting much deeper, curve it up and rise it to your mouth in a momentarily attained bourgeois fashion to eat another of this supposedly heavenly mixture.<br /><br />Holy smokes!! You are sent a mild ride around clouds and rainbows, and an extended play of orgasmic sensations pervades you and is visible on your face, of whose quality can only be initiated by pure arts!<br /><br />Just when you are about to plunge into the last part and main part, you feel as if you are biting something sour, as sour as it can get. But, this anti-villain, a wrong note in a culinary masterpiece has left a lasting sensation through it's wicked charm on u, and contrary to what should have happened, you keep tasting it to finish it, not out of obligation, but beyond human understanding. Like few peoples' addiction for souring quality in lemon.<br /> <br />You finish it with a sympathetic feeling for the toppings which had covered this dark wicked pieces.<br />Still the taste lingers, and you yet to recover from it and come back to your senses. You walk out only to run back to the menu card to find the name of the ice cream u had just enjoyed and you tip the server who nods happily. You walk out with such indescribable joy that you had never had felt before.<br /><br />This is how it was reading Boris Vian's "Froth on the daydream"<br /><br />This is not like other books where you walk into a store with your headphones adorning your ears and neck, and you casually take out your favorite Author's latest bestseller, or one that has been suggested by your so called "bibliophile" friend, which you can flaunt it to your like minded friends later. No! This is purely a serendipitous act, one sent by holy god to you. Probably the cover may have attracted you, or the title, or the description, or synopsis, or a review may have interested you.<br /><br />It may most certainly going to be there lying in your shelf ,without being touched by you post your buying. Someday you do take it out to see what this could offer, only to be blown away completely for it's various swing in moods, words, and imagery.<br /><br />But that is how this book has lived and will live. Such is its bittersweet fate is.<br /><br />Anyway, the book takes a usual love story --- people meeting accidentally with minor connections and falling in love at first sight. Vian for the most part has hinted at a fairy land setting with characters living like they pass their time at beaches. Characters are near perfect sketches of ideal humans without any slight cynicism, like innocent cute little dainties - naive and pure.<br /><br />He makes inanimate objects to take life by responding to characters mood - like a shrinking villa that responds to the mood of the character, or mouse acting like humans do.<br /><br />What makes this usual love story fresh and interesting is the fact that, Vian knows how to play with words, to create powerful imagery while throwing in a dash of light humour.<br /><br />The tone is muffled even when he could have played it more emotionally. <br />But, we feel for the characters because they are so genuine , that I found comparing them to Ozu's unbelievable believable characters.<br /><br />Novel takes a 180 degree turn in the last quarter; when finally those hanging in the air had to land to face the ground reality and cope with it, but only to be consumed by fate finally.<br /><br />It ends in a most bizzare fashion, that was reminiscent of Bergman's Seventh Seal climax, for its vivid visual description or the Yugoslavian black-wave marriage film "Lisice", for its mood and emotion, when the characters hike a hill when one of their guys has left them.<br /><br />Simple fact that there are more wonderful things that one can find in the novel, like the marvellous creation of Vian called "Pianococktail" which works in its own mechanism- where point of music and drinks flavors marry, makes it more deserving read than it has been bestowed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5813691793023571407" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


